// Unit 5: Hunger!
// Level: A1

const UNIT_5 =
{n:5,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Hunger!",sub:"Restaurant, modal verbs & dative prepositions",icon:"🍽️",level:"A1.1",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[

// ─── L1: Was gibt's zum Essen? ───
{id:"deu_r5l1",title:"Was gibt's zum Essen?",icon:"🍽️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Was gibt's zum Essen?",desc:"Learn the most important words for eating and drinking in Germany.",goals:["Name meals and food","Conjugate essen and trinken","Order at a restaurant"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-gasthaus-exterior-evening",trg:"Die Sonne geht unter in Neukölln. Verumius steht vor einem alten Gasthaus. Eine Kreidetafel steht neben der Tür.",src:"The sun is setting in Neukölln. Verumius stands in front of an old Gasthaus. A chalkboard stands beside the door."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"amused",art:"de-gasthaus-chalkboard",trg:"Auf der Tafel steht: Schweinebraten, Kartoffelpuffer, Rindergulaschsuppe. Verumius liest langsam. Sehr langsam.",src:"On the board it says: Schweinebraten, Kartoffelpuffer, Rindergulaschsuppe. Verumius reads slowly. Very slowly."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"overwhelmed",art:"de-gasthaus-chalkboard",trg:"Schweine... braten? Kartoffel... puffer? Das sind keine Wörter. Das sind ganze Sätze!",src:"Schweine... braten? Kartoffel... puffer? Those aren't words. Those are entire sentences!"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"determined",art:"de-gasthaus-exterior-evening",trg:"Ich habe Hunger. Ich gehe rein. Ich kann das.",src:"I'm hungry. I'm going in. I can do this."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Freund",src:"the friend (male)",note:"Masculine noun. Plural: die Freunde.\n'Mein Freund' can mean 'my boyfriend' or 'my male friend' depending on context.",example:"A: Wer ist Lukas?\nB: Lukas ist mein Freund. Wir essen zusammen.\nA: Ein guter Freund?",exampleSrc:"A: Who is Lukas?\nB: Lukas is my friend. We eat together.\nA: A good friend?",funFact:"'Freund' comes from the same root as English 'friend.' In Germany, being called 'ein Freund' means something deep. Germans distinguish between 'Bekannte' (acquaintances) and 'Freunde' (real friends). Making the jump takes time."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schön",src:"beautiful / nice / lovely",note:"One of the most common German adjectives.\nComparative: schöner. Superlative: am schönsten.",example:"A: Das Wetter ist heute schön!\nB: Ja, schön warm. Ein schöner Tag.\nA: Schön, dass du hier bist.",exampleSrc:"A: The weather is beautiful today!\nB: Yes, nicely warm. A beautiful day.\nA: Nice that you are here.",funFact:"Germans use 'schön' for everything: schönes Wetter (nice weather), schöne Grüße (kind regards), na schön (all right then), schön gemacht (well done). It is one of the five most common adjectives in German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Herz",src:"the heart",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Herzen.\nAlso used figuratively: 'von Herzen' = from the heart.",example:"A: Dieses Lied geht mir ans Herz.\nB: Mir auch. Es ist so schön.\nA: Von Herzen danke für den schönen Abend.",exampleSrc:"A: This song touches my heart.\nB: Mine too. It is so beautiful.\nA: Thank you from the heart for the lovely evening.",funFact:"Lebkuchenherz (gingerbread heart) is a classic German fair souvenir with icing messages like 'Ich liebe dich' or 'Schatz.' The word 'herzlich' (heartfelt, warm) comes from Herz. 'Herzlich willkommen!' = A heartfelt welcome!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Frühstück",src:"breakfast",note:"Neuter noun. From früh (early) + Stück (piece).",example:"A: Was gibt es zum Frühstück?\nB: Brötchen mit Käse und Marmelade.",exampleSrc:"A: What is there for breakfast?\nB: Rolls with cheese and jam.",funFact:"Germans take breakfast seriously. A typical Frühstück includes fresh rolls, cold cuts, cheese, jam, and a soft-boiled egg."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Mittag",src:"noon, midday",note:"Masculine noun. Also used in Mittagessen (lunch).",example:"A: Wann ist Mittag?\nB: Um zwölf Uhr.",exampleSrc:"A: When is noon?\nB: At twelve o'clock.",funFact:"Mittagessen is traditionally the biggest meal of the day in Germany, though this is changing in cities."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Abend",src:"evening",note:"Masculine noun. Abendessen means dinner or supper.",example:"A: Was machst du heute Abend?\nB: Ich koche Abendessen.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you doing this evening?\nB: I am cooking dinner.",funFact:"Abendbrot (evening bread) is a common light dinner of bread, cold cuts, and cheese."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which meal is traditionally the biggest in Germany?",opts:["das Frühstück","das Abendessen","das Mittagessen","das Abendbrot"],ans:"das Mittagessen",hint:"Think about the midday meal tradition."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Essen",src:"food, meal",note:"Neuter noun. Also means 'the eating' as a gerund.",example:"A: Wie ist das Essen hier?\nB: Das Essen ist sehr gut!",exampleSrc:"A: How is the food here?\nB: The food is very good!",funFact:"Das Essen can mean both the food itself and the act of eating. Context tells you which."},
{type:"teach",trg:"essen",src:"to eat",note:"Irregular verb: ich esse, du isst, er/sie isst. The vowel changes in du/er forms.",example:"A: Was isst du gern?\nB: Ich esse gern Brot mit Käse.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you like to eat?\nB: I like to eat bread with cheese.",funFact:"The vowel change e to i in du isst is a classic strong verb pattern in German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"trinken",src:"to drink",note:"Regular conjugation: ich trinke, du trinkst, er/sie trinkt.",example:"A: Was trinkst du?\nB: Ich trinke Kaffee.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you drinking?\nB: I am drinking coffee.",funFact:"Germans drink more coffee per capita than beer. About 162 liters of coffee per year!"},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} jeden Morgen ein Brötchen.",a:["esse"],opts:["esse","isst","essen","esst"],hint:"The vowel change only happens in du/er forms, not ich.",sSrc:"I eat a bread roll every morning."},
{type:"teach",trg:"frühstücken",src:"to have breakfast",note:"Regular verb formed from Frühstück + -en.",example:"A: Frühstückst du zu Hause?\nB: Nein, ich frühstücke im Büro.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have breakfast at home?\nB: No, I have breakfast at the office.",funFact:"Frühstücken is one of many German verbs made directly from a noun. Noun to verb, just add -en!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Appetit",src:"appetite",note:"Masculine noun. Used in the phrase Guten Appetit!",example:"A: Das Essen ist fertig!\nB: Wunderbar! Guten Appetit!",exampleSrc:"A: The food is ready!\nB: Wonderful! Enjoy your meal!",funFact:"Saying Guten Appetit before eating is essential etiquette in Germany. Not saying it is considered rude."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Speisekarte",src:"menu",note:"Feminine noun. Speise (dish) + Karte (card).",example:"A: Kann ich bitte die Speisekarte haben?\nB: Natürlich, hier bitte.",exampleSrc:"A: Can I have the menu please?\nB: Of course, here you go.",funFact:"In Germany, you often have to ask for the menu. It is not always brought automatically."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Speisenkarte",src:"menu (variant spelling)",note:"Feminine noun. Same meaning as Speisekarte, with an extra -n-.",example:"A: Haben Sie eine Speisenkarte?\nB: Ja, einen Moment bitte.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a menu?\nB: Yes, one moment please.",funFact:"Both Speisekarte and Speisenkarte are correct. You will see both in restaurants across Germany."},
{type:"mc",q:"What do Germans say before eating a meal?",opts:["Guten Appetit!","Guten Morgen!","Guten Tag!","Guten Abend!"],ans:"Guten Appetit!",hint:"It involves a word you just learned about hunger and food."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Zigarette",src:"cigarette",note:"Feminine noun. Borrowed from French.",example:"A: Rauchst du?\nB: Nein, ich rauche keine Zigaretten.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you smoke?\nB: No, I do not smoke cigarettes.",funFact:"Smoking is banned in restaurants and bars across Germany since 2007, though rules vary by state."},
{type:"teach",trg:"rauchen",src:"to smoke",note:"Regular verb: ich rauche, du rauchst, er/sie raucht.",example:"A: Darf man hier rauchen?\nB: Nein, rauchen ist hier verboten.",exampleSrc:"A: Is smoking allowed here?\nB: No, smoking is forbidden here.",funFact:"The word Rauch also means smoke as a noun. Räucherlachs (smoked salmon) uses the same root."},
{type:"fb",s:"Kann ich bitte die {1} haben?",a:["Speisekarte"],opts:["Speisekarte","Essen","Appetit","Frühstück"],hint:"You are asking for something to read before ordering.",sSrc:"Can I please have the menu?"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"das Frühstück",src:"breakfast"},{trg:"der Mittag",src:"noon"},{trg:"der Abend",src:"evening"},{trg:"trinken",src:"to drink"},{trg:"die Speisekarte",src:"menu"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich ___ gern Brot. Which form of essen fits?",opts:["isst","esse","esst","essen"],ans:"esse",hint:"The subject is ich. What happens to the vowel?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Guten {1}! Das Essen sieht lecker aus.",a:["Appetit"],opts:["Appetit","Morgen","Abend","Tag"],hint:"A polite phrase said before meals.",sSrc:"Enjoy your meal! The food looks delicious."},
{type:"tip",title:"Im Gasthaus",text:"A Gasthaus is a traditional German inn or restaurant. When you arrive:\n1. Wait to be seated or find a free table.\n2. Ask: Kann ich die Speisekarte haben?\n3. Say Guten Appetit before eating.\n4. To pay: Zahlen bitte! or Die Rechnung bitte!",deepDive:{title:"Restaurant culture",text:"In Germany, tipping is not as high as in the US. Rounding up or adding 5 to 10 percent is normal. You say the total amount you want to pay, including tip, when handing money to the server."}},
{type:"mc",q:"Which word means the same as Speisekarte?",opts:["Rechnung","Bestellung","Speisenkarte","Kellner"],ans:"Speisenkarte",hint:"It is a variant spelling with one extra letter."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"gentle",art:"de-gasthaus-exterior-door",trg:"Verumius atmet tief ein. Dann öffnet er die Tür.",src:"Verumius takes a deep breath. Then he opens the door."}
]},

// ─── L2: Wie schmeckt's? ───
{id:"deu_r5l2",title:"Wie schmeckt's?",icon:"😋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Wie schmeckt's?",desc:"Learn adjectives for taste, mood, and preferences. Express what you like and what appeals to you.",goals:["Adjectives for taste and mood","Use gern/gerne","Distinguish between gefallen and lieben"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"cozy",art:"de-gasthaus-interior-wide",trg:"Drinnen ist es warm. Es riecht nach Brot und Braten. Holztische, karierte Tischdecken, alte Bierkrüge an der Wand.",src:"Inside it's warm. It smells of bread and roast meat. Wooden tables, checkered tablecloths, old beer steins on the wall."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wunderbar",src:"wonderful",note:"Adjective/adverb. Works the same way as English wonderful.",example:"A: Wie schmeckt die Suppe?\nB: Wunderbar! Wirklich lecker.",exampleSrc:"A: How does the soup taste?\nB: Wonderful! Really delicious.",funFact:"Wunderbar became internationally famous through the Kinder chocolate bar of the same name."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schlecht",src:"bad",note:"Adjective. Opposite of gut (good).",example:"A: Wie geht es dir?\nB: Mir geht es schlecht. Ich bin krank.",exampleSrc:"A: How are you?\nB: I am doing badly. I am sick.",funFact:"Schlechtes Wetter (bad weather) is a very common phrase in Germany. Germans love talking about weather."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einfach",src:"simple, easy",note:"Adjective/adverb. Also used as 'just' or 'simply'.",example:"A: Ist Deutsch schwer?\nB: Nein, es ist einfach!",exampleSrc:"A: Is German hard?\nB: No, it is easy!",funFact:"Einfach also means 'one-way' for tickets. Eine einfache Fahrkarte is a one-way ticket."},
{type:"teach",trg:"lustig",src:"funny, fun",note:"Adjective. Not to be confused with English 'lusty'.",example:"A: Der Film war sehr lustig.\nB: Ja, ich habe viel gelacht!",exampleSrc:"A: The film was very funny.\nB: Yes, I laughed a lot!",funFact:"Lustig is a false friend. It means funny, not lustful. The German word for lustful is lüstern."},
{type:"mc",q:"Das Essen ist ___! Ich liebe es! Which word fits best?",opts:["wunderbar","schlecht","bitter","laut"],ans:"wunderbar",hint:"The speaker loves the food. Pick the positive word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"laut",src:"loud",note:"Adjective. Opposite of leise.",example:"A: Die Musik ist zu laut!\nB: Entschuldigung, ich mache sie leiser.",exampleSrc:"A: The music is too loud!\nB: Sorry, I will turn it down.",funFact:"Laut also means 'according to' as a preposition: laut dem Bericht (according to the report)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"leise",src:"quiet, soft (sound)",note:"Adjective. Describes low volume, not personality.",example:"A: Kannst du bitte leise sein?\nB: Entschuldigung, ich bin schon still.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you please be quiet?\nB: Sorry, I am already silent.",funFact:"Leise Töne means subtle hints. Germans use leise figuratively for anything understated."},
{type:"teach",trg:"ruhig",src:"calm, peaceful",note:"Adjective. Describes a calm atmosphere or person.",example:"A: Wie ist das Restaurant?\nB: Sehr ruhig und gemütlich.",exampleSrc:"A: How is the restaurant?\nB: Very calm and cozy.",funFact:"Ruhig also works as a particle meaning 'go ahead': Du kannst ruhig fragen means Feel free to ask."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Bibliothek ist sehr {1}. Man hört nichts.",a:["ruhig"],opts:["ruhig","laut","lustig","schlecht"],hint:"A library is a peaceful, quiet place.",sSrc:"The library is very quiet. You can't hear anything."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bitter",src:"bitter",note:"Adjective. Same word in English and German.",example:"A: Wie schmeckt der Kaffee?\nB: Er ist ein bisschen bitter.",exampleSrc:"A: How does the coffee taste?\nB: It is a little bitter.",funFact:"Bitterschokolade is dark chocolate in German. Literally: bitter chocolate."},
{type:"teach",trg:"lecker",src:"delicious / yummy",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"The most common positive food word in German.\nLecker alone = Yum! Very natural in any food context.",example:"A: Wie ist die Suppe?\nB: Lecker! Sehr lecker!",exampleSrc:"A: How is the soup?\nB: Delicious! Very delicious!",funFact:"In Northern German dialects, 'lecker' used to mean 'leaky.' The meaning 'delicious' spread from Southern Germany. Now everyone uses it for tasty food."},
{type:"teach",trg:"salzig",src:"salty",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Salz (salt) + -ig. Describes food with too much or just right salt.",example:"A: Wie schmeckt die Suppe?\nB: Etwas zu salzig, aber sonst gut.",exampleSrc:"A: How does the soup taste?\nB: A bit too salty, but otherwise good.",funFact:"The -ig ending turns many nouns into adjectives: Salz to salzig, Hunger to hungrig, Durst to durstig."},
{type:"tip",title:"Schmeckt + Taste Description",text:"Es schmeckt gut. = It tastes good.\nEs schmeckt lecker. = It tastes delicious.\nEs schmeckt zu salzig. = It tastes too salty.\n\nPattern: Es schmeckt + adjective.\n\nPersonal preference:\nIch mag Fisch. = I like fish.\nIch esse gern Fisch. = I like eating fish.\ngern with a verb = gladly = expressing liking.",deepDive:{title:"The schmecken verb",text:"Schmecken works differently from English 'taste':\n\nEs schmeckt. = It tastes good. (no adjective needed!)\nEs schmeckt mir. = I like how it tastes. (dative!)\nWie schmeckt es? = How does it taste?\n\nIf a German says 'Es schmeckt!' about your cooking, that is the highest compliment. No adjective required."}},
{type:"teach",trg:"zufrieden",src:"satisfied, content",note:"Adjective. Often used with mit (with).",example:"A: Bist du zufrieden mit dem Essen?\nB: Ja, sehr zufrieden!",exampleSrc:"A: Are you satisfied with the food?\nB: Yes, very satisfied!",funFact:"Zufrieden comes from zu (to) + Frieden (peace). Being satisfied literally means being at peace."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zusammen",src:"together",note:"Adverb. Also used when paying: zusammen oder getrennt?",example:"A: Zusammen oder getrennt?\nB: Zusammen bitte.",exampleSrc:"A: Together or separate?\nB: Together please.",funFact:"In Germany, waiters always ask zusammen oder getrennt? (together or separate?) when you want to pay."},
{type:"mc",q:"The waiter asks: Zusammen oder getrennt? What is being asked?",opts:["One bill or separate bills","Eat in or take away","Cash or card","Smoking or non-smoking"],ans:"One bill or separate bills",hint:"Zusammen = together. Getrennt = ___. The waiter asks about the check."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gern",src:"gladly, with pleasure",note:"Adverb. Used with verbs to express liking: Ich koche gern.",example:"A: Kochst du gern?\nB: Ja, ich koche sehr gern!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like cooking?\nB: Yes, I really like cooking!",funFact:"Gern is the short form. Gerne means exactly the same thing. Both are equally correct."},
{type:"teach",trg:"gerne",src:"gladly, with pleasure",note:"Adverb. Longer form of gern, identical in meaning.",example:"A: Möchtest du Kaffee?\nB: Ja, gerne!",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like coffee?\nB: Yes, gladly!",funFact:"Gerne! by itself is a common reply meaning Yes please! or With pleasure!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"gefallen",src:"to please, to like (something pleases you)",note:"The thing liked is the subject: Das Buch gefällt mir (The book pleases me).",example:"A: Gefällt dir das Restaurant?\nB: Ja, es gefällt mir sehr gut!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like the restaurant?\nB: Yes, I like it a lot!",funFact:"Gefallen flips the subject. You do not like the book. The book likes you. This confuses many learners at first."},
{type:"teach",trg:"lieben",src:"to love",note:"Regular verb: ich liebe, du liebst. Stronger than mögen or gern.",example:"A: Liebst du Schokolade?\nB: Ja, ich liebe Schokolade!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you love chocolate?\nB: Yes, I love chocolate!",funFact:"Ich liebe dich (I love you) is one of the most searched German phrases worldwide."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich schwimme {1}. Es macht Spaß!",a:["gern"],opts:["gern","schlecht","bitter","laut"],hint:"You enjoy swimming. Which adverb expresses liking an activity?",sSrc:"I like to swim. It is fun!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Das Buch gefällt mir. What is the subject of this sentence?",opts:["Me / I","The pleasure","The book","Nobody"],ans:"The book",hint:"In gefallen sentences, the thing that pleases is the grammatical subject."},
{type:"tip",title:"gern vs gefallen vs lieben",text:"Three ways to say you like something:\n1. gern/gerne + verb: Ich lese gern. (I like reading.)\n2. gefallen + dative: Das gefällt mir. (That pleases me.)\n3. lieben: Ich liebe Musik. (I love music.)\n\ngern is for activities, gefallen is for impressions, lieben is the strongest.",deepDive:{title:"Why gefallen flips the subject",text:"Gefallen literally means 'to please.' The thing you like is doing the pleasing, so it becomes the subject. Das Essen gefällt mir = The food pleases me. If you want to say 'I like the food,' the German structure puts the food first as the subject and you in the dative case (mir)."}},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"wunderbar",src:"wonderful"},{trg:"schlecht",src:"bad"},{trg:"lustig",src:"funny"},{trg:"leise",src:"quiet"},{trg:"zufrieden",src:"satisfied"},{trg:"zusammen",src:"together"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Film ist sehr {1}. Alle lachen.",a:["lustig"],opts:["lustig","leise","bitter","ruhig"],hint:"Everyone is laughing. The film must be funny.",sSrc:"The film is very funny. Everyone is laughing."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich koche gern. What does this sentence mean?",opts:["I cook well.","I must cook.","I am cooking.","I like cooking."],ans:"I like cooking.",hint:"Gern after a verb expresses enjoyment of that activity."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"anticipating",art:"de-gasthaus-interior-table",trg:"Ein Kellner zeigt auf den letzten freien Platz. An dem Tisch sitzt schon jemand.",src:"A waiter points to the last free seat. Someone is already sitting at that table."}
]},

// ─── L3: Ich kann das nicht lesen! ───
{id:"deu_r5l3",title:"Ich kann das nicht lesen!",icon:"📖",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Ich kann das nicht lesen!",desc:"Learn the three most important modal verbs: können, müssen, wollen. Discover how they change sentence structure.",goals:["Conjugate können, müssen, wollen","Understand modal verb sentence structure","Express wishes and obligations"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"surprised",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-table",trg:"Es ist der Typ vom Imbiss. Fahrradhelm auf dem Tisch. Courier-Rucksack auf dem Boden. Er grinst.",src:"It's the guy from the Imbiss. Bike helmet on the table. Courier backpack on the floor. He's grinning."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"casual",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-table",trg:"Hey! Du bist doch der Neue aus der Schillerstraße, oder? Setz dich!",src:"Hey! You're the new guy from Schillerstraße, right? Sit down!"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"shy",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-table",trg:"Ja, hallo! Entschuldigung, kennen wir uns?",src:"Yes, hello! Sorry, do we know each other?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"grinning",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-close",trg:"Klar! Imbiss, letzte Woche. Du hast drei Minuten die Karte angestarrt. Ich bin Lukas.",src:"Sure! Imbiss, last week. You stared at the menu for three minutes. I'm Lukas."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"embarrassed",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-table",trg:"Oh. Ja. Das war ich. Ich bin Verumius.",src:"Oh. Yes. That was me. I'm Verumius."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"friendly",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-close",trg:"Verumius? Krasser Name, Alter. Okay, hör zu. Sag einfach: Ich hätte gern... und dann zeig auf die Karte. Fertig.",src:"Verumius? Wild name, dude. Okay, listen. Just say: Ich hätte gern... and then point at the menu. Done."},
{type:"teach",trg:"können",src:"can, to be able to",note:"Modal verb. Irregular: ich kann, du kannst, er kann. Infinitive goes to end.",example:"A: Kannst du Deutsch sprechen?\nB: Ja, ich kann ein bisschen Deutsch sprechen.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you speak German?\nB: Yes, I can speak a little German.",funFact:"Können changes its vowel from ö to a in singular forms. This pattern is typical for German modal verbs."},
{type:"teach",trg:"müssen",src:"must, to have to",note:"Modal verb. Irregular: ich muss, du musst, er muss. Expresses necessity.",example:"A: Musst du morgen arbeiten?\nB: Ja, ich muss um acht Uhr anfangen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have to work tomorrow?\nB: Yes, I have to start at eight o'clock.",funFact:"Nicht müssen means 'do not have to,' not 'must not.' This catches many English speakers off guard."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wollen",src:"to want",note:"Modal verb. Irregular: ich will, du willst, er will. Expresses desire.",example:"A: Was willst du essen?\nB: Ich will Pizza bestellen.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you want to eat?\nB: I want to order pizza.",funFact:"German ich will sounds like English 'I will,' but means 'I want.' Will for future is ich werde."},
{type:"tip",title:"Modal verb sentence structure",text:"Modal verbs change word order:\n1. The modal verb is conjugated and takes position 2.\n2. The main verb goes to the END in infinitive form.\n\nIch spreche Deutsch. (normal)\nIch kann Deutsch sprechen. (with modal)\n\nThe modal is conjugated, the main verb stays infinitive at the end.",deepDive:{title:"Why the verb goes to the end",text:"German has a verb bracket (Satzklammer). The conjugated verb stays in position 2, but any additional verb forms move to the end. This creates a bracket around the middle of the sentence. With modals: Ich [kann] heute Abend nicht [kommen]. The modal opens the bracket, the infinitive closes it."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"können (can)",groups:[{label:"Present tense",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"kann",src:"I can"},{pronoun:"du",form:"kannst",src:"you can"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"kann",src:"he/she/it can"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"können",src:"we can"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"könnt",src:"you all can"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"können",src:"they/you (formal) can"}]}],note:"Notice: ich and er/sie/es have the same form (kann). The vowel changes from ö to a in singular."},
{type:"mc",q:"Du ___ sehr gut kochen! Which form of können fits?",opts:["kann","können","kannst","könnt"],ans:"kannst",hint:"The subject is du. Add -st to the singular stem."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} Deutsch sprechen.",a:["kann"],opts:["kann","kannst","können","könnt"],hint:"First person singular of können.",sSrc:"I can speak German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verboten",src:"forbidden, prohibited",note:"Adjective/past participle. From verbieten (to forbid).",example:"A: Darf ich hier rauchen?\nB: Nein, das ist verboten!",exampleSrc:"A: May I smoke here?\nB: No, that is forbidden!",funFact:"Verboten signs are everywhere in Germany. Germans are known for following rules, and these signs are taken seriously."},
{type:"verb_table",title:"müssen (must)",groups:[{label:"Present tense",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"muss",src:"I must"},{pronoun:"du",form:"musst",src:"you must"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"muss",src:"he/she/it must"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"müssen",src:"we must"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"müsst",src:"you all must"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"müssen",src:"they/you (formal) must"}]}],note:"Same pattern: ü to u in singular. ich and er/sie/es share the same form (muss)."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wir ___ um 8 Uhr da sein. Which modal verb fits?",opts:["müssen","muss","musst","müsst"],ans:"müssen",hint:"The subject is wir. Use the plural form."},
{type:"teach",trg:"lieb",src:"dear, sweet, kind",note:"Adjective. Used for people: ein liebes Kind (a sweet child).",example:"A: Dein Sohn ist sehr lieb.\nB: Danke, das ist nett von dir!",exampleSrc:"A: Your son is very sweet.\nB: Thanks, that is nice of you!",funFact:"Lieb is related to lieben (to love). Liebling means darling or favorite."},
{type:"teach",trg:"böse",src:"angry, evil, naughty",note:"Adjective. Context determines the meaning: angry (person) or evil (character).",example:"A: Bist du böse auf mich?\nB: Nein, ich bin nicht böse.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you angry with me?\nB: No, I am not angry.",funFact:"Böse auf means angry at someone. Der Böse means the villain. The Brothers Grimm used böse for all their fairy tale villains."},
{type:"verb_table",title:"wollen (to want)",groups:[{label:"Present tense",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"will",src:"I want"},{pronoun:"du",form:"willst",src:"you want"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"will",src:"he/she/it wants"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"wollen",src:"we want"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"wollt",src:"you all want"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"wollen",src:"they/you (formal) want"}]}],note:"Vowel change o to i in singular. Remember: will means want, not future tense!"},
{type:"fb",s:"Er {1} heute Abend ins Kino gehen.",a:["will"],opts:["will","wollen","wollt","willst"],hint:"Third person singular of wollen.",sSrc:"He wants to go to the cinema tonight."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich kann Deutsch ___. Where does the infinitive go?",opts:["sprechen (after ich)","spreche (at the end)","gesprochen (at the end)","sprechen (at the end)"],ans:"sprechen (at the end)",hint:"With modal verbs, the main verb goes to the end in infinitive form."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Wir {1} heute Abend Pizza {2}.",blanks:{"1":"müssen","2":"essen"},pool:["müssen","essen","muss","isst"],hint:"We have to eat pizza tonight. Modal in position 2, main verb at end.",sSrc:"We must eat pizza tonight."},
{type:"mc",q:"Ich muss nicht arbeiten. What does this mean?",opts:["I must not work.","I cannot work.","I do not have to work.","I will not work."],ans:"I do not have to work.",hint:"Nicht müssen means lack of obligation, not prohibition."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} eine Bratwurst bestellen.",a:["will"],opts:["will","kann","muss","wollen"],hint:"You want to order a sausage. Which modal expresses desire?",sSrc:"I want to order a bratwurst."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Sie {1} gut Deutsch {2} und {3} mehr {4}.",blanks:{"1":"kann","2":"sprechen","3":"will","4":"lernen"},pool:["kann","sprechen","will","lernen","muss","können"],hint:"She can speak German well and wants to learn more. Two modal clauses joined.",sSrc:"She can speak German well and wants to learn more."},
{type:"mc",q:"Kannst du das ___? I cannot read it!",opts:["verboten","müssen","verstehen","lieb"],ans:"verstehen",hint:"The speaker cannot read something and asks if you can understand it."},
{type:"tip",title:"Zusammengesetzte Wörter",text:"German is famous for compound words:\n\nSpeise + Karte = Speisekarte (menu)\nFrüh + Stück = Frühstück (breakfast)\nAbend + Essen = Abendessen (dinner)\nMittag + Essen = Mittagessen (lunch)\n\nThe last word determines the gender: die Karte, so die Speisekarte.",deepDive:{title:"The longest German words",text:"German compounds can get very long. Rindfleischetikettierungsüberwachungsaufgabenübertragungsgesetz was an actual law about beef labeling. The rule is simple: take any nouns, stick them together, and the last noun gives the gender and plural form."}},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"hopeful",art:"de-gasthaus-interior-table",trg:"Ich hätte gern... Okay. Das kann ich mir merken.",src:"Ich hätte gern... Okay. I can remember that."}
]},

// ─── L4: Darf ich? Soll ich? Möchtest du? ───
{id:"deu_r5l4",title:"Darf ich? Soll ich? Möchtest du?",icon:"🎭",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Darf ich? Soll ich? Möchtest du?",desc:"Three more modal verbs complete the set. Permission, obligation, and the politest way to order anything in Germany.",goals:["dürfen (permission), sollen (should), mögen (like)","möchten: the polite ordering form","Comparatives: besser, lieber, am besten"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"observant",art:"de-gasthaus-menu-close",trg:"Verumius hält die Speisekarte. Lukas beugt sich rüber und zeigt auf die Gerichte.",src:"Verumius holds the menu. Lukas leans over and points at the dishes."},
{type:"teach",trg:"dürfen",src:"may / to be allowed to",note:"The permission modal. 'Darf ich?' = May I?",example:"A: Darf ich hier sitzen?\nB: Ja, natürlich!",exampleSrc:"A: May I sit here?\nB: Yes, of course!",funFact:"'Nicht dürfen' = must not / forbidden. 'Nicht müssen' = don't have to. Critical difference! Mixing them up causes chaos."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sollen",src:"should / to be supposed to",note:"For advice and expectations. 'Du sollst nicht stehlen.'",example:"A: Soll ich bestellen?\nB: Ja, bitte!",exampleSrc:"A: Should I order?\nB: Yes, please!",funFact:"Used for advice, expectations, and reported instructions. Less about personal desire, more about what others expect."},
{type:"teach",trg:"mögen",src:"to like (general)",note:"'Ich mag Kaffee.' Subjunctive 'möchten' = would like.",example:"A: Magst du Fisch?\nB: Ja, ich mag Fisch sehr!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like fish?\nB: Yes, I like fish a lot!",funFact:"'Mögen' = general liking. 'Möchten' (would like) is the REAL star: the politest way to order. 'Ich möchte einen Kaffee, bitte.'"},
{type:"verb_table",title:"dürfen / sollen / mögen",groups:[{label:"dürfen (may)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"darf",src:"I may"},{pronoun:"du",form:"darfst",src:"you may"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"darf",src:"he/she/it may"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"dürfen",src:"we may"}]},{label:"sollen (should)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"soll",src:"I should"},{pronoun:"du",form:"sollst",src:"you should"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"soll",src:"he/she/it should"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"sollen",src:"we should"}]},{label:"mögen / möchten",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"mag / möchte",src:"I like / I'd like"},{pronoun:"du",form:"magst / möchtest",src:"you like / you'd like"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"mag / möchte",src:"likes / would like"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"mögen / möchten",src:"we like / we'd like"}]}],note:"All three: no ending on ich/er forms. Möchten is THE polite ordering form."},
{type:"tip",title:"dürfen nicht vs müssen nicht",text:"These two look similar but mean OPPOSITE things:\n\ndürfen nicht = MUST NOT (forbidden)\nDu darfst hier nicht rauchen. = You must not smoke here.\n\nmüssen nicht = DON'T HAVE TO (no obligation)\nDu musst nicht kommen. = You don't have to come.\n\nMixing them up creates serious misunderstandings!",deepDive:{title:"The deadly modal mix-up",text:"English 'must not' = German 'dürfen nicht' (forbidden)\nEnglish 'don't have to' = German 'müssen nicht' (optional)\n\nIf someone says 'Du darfst das nicht!' they are forbidding you.\nIf someone says 'Du musst das nicht.' they are releasing you from obligation.\n\nThis distinction is strict in German. Using the wrong one can make you sound either too controlling or too permissive."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'Darf ich hier rauchen?' asks about:",opts:["Am I allowed to smoke here?","Must I smoke here?","Should I smoke here?","Do I want to smoke here?"],ans:"Am I allowed to smoke here?",hint:"Dürfen is about permission."},
{type:"fb",s:"Man {1} hier nicht rauchen. Es ist verboten!",a:["darf"],opts:["darf","soll","muss","kann"],hint:"Permission denied = prohibition. Not ability.",sSrc:"One may not smoke here. It is forbidden!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"besser",src:"better (comparative of gut)",note:"Irregular: gut, besser, am besten.",example:"A: Wie ist das Restaurant?\nB: Besser als gestern!",exampleSrc:"A: How is the restaurant?\nB: Better than yesterday!",funFact:"Gut, besser, am besten. Irregular just like English 'good, better, best.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"lieber",src:"rather / preferably (comparative of gern)",note:"'Ich esse lieber Fisch' = I prefer eating fish.",example:"A: Trinkst du lieber Bier oder Wein?\nB: Ich trinke lieber Wein.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you prefer beer or wine?\nB: I prefer wine.",funFact:"If gern = gladly, lieber = more gladly = preferably. Express preferences effortlessly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"am besten",src:"best (superlative of gut)",note:"'Das ist das beste Restaurant!' Irregular superlative.",example:"A: Welches Essen ist am besten?\nB: Der Schweinebraten ist am besten!",exampleSrc:"A: Which food is the best?\nB: The pork roast is the best!",funFact:"'Am besten' = best of all. The superlative of the irregular gut-besser-best chain."},
{type:"mc",q:"Lukas: '___ du den Schweinebraten?'",opts:["Willst","Darfst","Sollst","Möchtest"],ans:"Möchtest",hint:"Lukas is being polite. Which modal is the politest offer?"},
{type:"tip",title:"The 6 Modal Verbs: Complete Set",text:"können: ability (I CAN swim)\nmüssen: necessity (I MUST eat)\nwollen: desire (I WANT that)\ndürfen: permission (MAY I?)\nsollen: expectation (I SHOULD help)\nmögen/möchten: liking / polite want\n\nAll follow the same pattern:\n1. Conjugated modal in position 2\n2. Main verb as infinitive at the END\n3. No ending on ich and er/sie/es forms",deepDive:{title:"The Satzklammer (sentence bracket)",text:"The core frame for all modals:\n\nSubject + Modal (pos. 2) + [middle field] + Infinitive (END)\n\nIch kann gut Deutsch sprechen.\nWir müssen jetzt gehen.\nDu darfst hier nicht rauchen.\n\nNotice: negation (nicht), adverbs (jetzt, gut), and objects all go in the middle field. The infinitive is always LAST. This bracket structure is called the Satzklammer and is one of the most important patterns in German word order."}},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} ich Ihnen etwas empfehlen?",a:["Darf"],opts:["Darf","Muss","Wird","Hat"],hint:"The waiter is asking for permission to make a suggestion.",sSrc:"May I recommend something to you?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} den Fisch, aber Lukas {2} lieber den Schweinebraten {3}.",blanks:{"1":"möchte","2":"will","3":"essen"},pool:["möchte","will","essen","kann","trinken","muss"],hint:"One speaker is polite, the other is direct. Use two different modals.",sSrc:"I would like the fish, but Lukas wants to eat the pork roast."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which expression means 'must not' (forbidden)?",opts:["nicht müssen","nicht sollen","nicht dürfen","nicht können"],ans:"nicht dürfen",hint:"To forbid something, you negate the permission modal."},
{type:"fb",s:"Du {1} mehr Wasser trinken. Das ist gesund.",a:["sollst"],opts:["sollst","darfst","willst","magst"],hint:"Friendly advice: what you SHOULD do.",sSrc:"You should drink more water. That is healthy."},
{type:"mc",q:"Most polite way to order:",opts:["Ich will einen Kaffee.","Gib mir einen Kaffee.","Ich muss einen Kaffee haben.","Ich möchte einen Kaffee, bitte."],ans:"Ich möchte einen Kaffee, bitte.",hint:"The subjunctive form of mögen is the most polite way to order."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Man {1} hier nicht rauchen, aber man {2} draußen {3}.",blanks:{"1":"darf","2":"kann","3":"rauchen"},pool:["darf","kann","rauchen","muss","soll","trinken"],hint:"MAY NOT inside, but CAN outside. Permission vs ability.",sSrc:"One may not smoke here, but one can smoke outside."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich esse lieber Fisch.' Lieber expresses:",opts:["preference","love","permission","ability"],ans:"preference",hint:"Lieber is comparative of gern. More gladly = preferably."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Essen hier ist {1} als im anderen Restaurant.",a:["besser"],opts:["besser","lieber","best","wunderbar"],hint:"Comparing two things. Comparative of gut.",sSrc:"The food here is better than at the other restaurant."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Restaurant ist am ___?",opts:["besser","gut","besten","lieber"],ans:"besten",hint:"Superlative with 'am': am + ___en. Best of all."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Lukas {1} Bier, aber er {2} heute lieber Wasser {3}.",blanks:{"1":"mag","2":"möchte","3":"trinken"},pool:["mag","möchte","trinken","kann","will","essen"],hint:"He LIKES beer general. Today he'd LIKE to drink water.",sSrc:"Lukas likes beer, but today he would like to drink water."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"können",src:"can/able to"},{trg:"müssen",src:"must/have to"},{trg:"wollen",src:"to want"},{trg:"dürfen",src:"may/allowed"},{trg:"sollen",src:"should"},{trg:"mögen",src:"to like"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"encouraging",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-close",trg:"Soll ich bestellen? Oder möchtest du das selbst machen? Ich warte.",src:"Should I order? Or do you want to do it yourself? I'll wait."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"brave",art:"de-gasthaus-interior-table",trg:"Nein, nein. Ich mache das. Ich möchte das lernen.",src:"No, no. I'll do it. I want to learn this."}
]},

// ─── L5: Ich bestelle für uns beide! ───
{id:"deu_r5l5",title:"Ich bestelle für uns beide!",icon:"📋",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Ich bestelle für uns beide!",desc:"Lukas takes charge. Restaurant action verbs and separable verbs at the table. Time to order like a pro.",goals:["Restaurant action verbs","Separable verbs: mitbringen, mitnehmen","Order food confidently"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"tense",art:"de-gasthaus-waiter-approaching",trg:"Der Kellner kommt. Stift und Block in der Hand. Er wartet.",src:"The waiter comes. Pen and notepad in hand. He waits."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"nervous",art:"de-gasthaus-waiter-approaching",trg:"Ich hätte gern... den... Kartoffelpuffer? Und ein Wasser, bitte.",src:"I would like... the... Kartoffelpuffer? And a water, please."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"proud",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-close",trg:"Digga! Perfekt! Für mich das Schnitzel und ein Bier, danke.",src:"Dude! Perfect! For me the Schnitzel and a beer, thanks."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bestellen",src:"to order",note:"Regular. 'Ich möchte bestellen' = I'd like to order.",example:"A: Kann ich bitte bestellen?\nB: Natürlich! Was möchten Sie?",exampleSrc:"A: Can I please order?\nB: Of course! What would you like?",funFact:"The single most important restaurant verb. Waiters ask 'Haben Sie schon bestellt?' (Have you already ordered?)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"empfehlen",src:"to recommend",note:"Irregular: ich empfehle, du empfiehlst, er empfiehlt.",example:"A: Was empfehlen Sie?\nB: Ich empfehle den Schweinebraten!",exampleSrc:"A: What do you recommend?\nB: I recommend the pork roast!",funFact:"Vowel change e to ie. 'Was empfehlen Sie?' is the perfect question when the menu is incomprehensible."},
{type:"verb_table",title:"empfehlen (to recommend)",groups:[{label:"Present tense (stem change: e → ie)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"empfehle",src:"I recommend"},{pronoun:"du",form:"empfiehlst",src:"you recommend"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"empfiehlt",src:"he/she/it recommends"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"empfehlen",src:"we recommend"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"empfehlt",src:"you all recommend"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"empfehlen",src:"they/you (formal) recommend"}]}],note:"Same e → ie pattern as lesen (liest)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schmecken",src:"to taste",note:"'Schmeckt's?' = Does it taste good? Highest food compliment.",example:"A: Wie schmeckt das Essen?\nB: Es schmeckt wunderbar!",exampleSrc:"A: How does the food taste?\nB: It tastes wonderful!",funFact:"'Schmeckt's?' is how every German grandma checks on you mid-meal. 'Es schmeckt!' needs no object. It just tastes good."},
{type:"mc",q:"The waiter asks: 'Was ___ Sie?' What is he asking?",opts:["möchten","schmecken","empfehlen","riechen"],ans:"möchten",hint:"He wants to know what you'd like to order."},
{type:"teach",trg:"kochen",src:"to cook",note:"Regular. Also means 'to boil': Das Wasser kocht.",example:"A: Kannst du kochen?\nB: Ja, ich koche gern!",exampleSrc:"A: Can you cook?\nB: Yes, I like cooking!",funFact:"'Kochen' also means 'to boil.' 'Das Wasser kocht' = the water is boiling. A versatile kitchen verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"riechen",src:"to smell",note:"Irregular: riechen, roch, gerochen. Present tense is regular.",example:"A: Das Essen riecht gut!\nB: Ja, der Koch ist sehr gut.",exampleSrc:"A: The food smells good!\nB: Yes, the cook is very good.",funFact:"'Das riecht gut!' is what you say walking past a Bäckerei. German noses are well-trained."},
{type:"teach",trg:"grillen",src:"to grill / to barbecue",note:"Regular. A national summer sport in Germany.",example:"A: Wollen wir am Samstag grillen?\nB: Ja, ich bringe Würstchen mit!",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we grill on Saturday?\nB: Yes, I'll bring sausages!",funFact:"Germans LOVE grilling. Parks fill with smoke every warm Saturday. It is always charcoal, never gas. That is a rule."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Essen {1} fantastisch! Der Koch ist toll.",a:["riecht"],opts:["riecht","schmeckt","kocht","bestellt"],hint:"You haven't eaten yet. You are using your nose.",sSrc:"The food smells fantastic! The cook is great."},
{type:"teach",trg:"mitbringen",src:"to bring along",note:"Separable: ich bringe Wein mit. Prefix goes to the end.",example:"A: Ich bringe Kuchen mit.\nB: Super! Ich freue mich.",exampleSrc:"A: I'll bring cake.\nB: Great! I'm looking forward to it.",funFact:"'Bring bitte Brot mit!' is a common request. Separable: the 'mit' goes to the end."},
{type:"teach",trg:"mitnehmen",src:"to take along / to go",note:"Separable: ich nehme den Kaffee mit. 'Zum Mitnehmen' = to go.",example:"A: Zum Mitnehmen, bitte.\nB: Kommt sofort!",exampleSrc:"A: To go, please.\nB: Coming right up!",funFact:"'Zum Mitnehmen' is how you order food to go in Germany. Mit (along) + nehmen (take)."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Zum Mitnehmen' means:",opts:["for here","for two people","to go / take away","without tip"],ans:"to go / take away",hint:"'Mit' = along, 'nehmen' = to take. Take along."},
{type:"fb",s:"Was {1} der Kellner heute?",a:["empfiehlt"],opts:["empfiehlt","bestellt","kocht","schmeckt"],hint:"The waiter is suggesting something. Vowel change: e to ie.",sSrc:"What does the waiter recommend today?"},
{type:"tip",title:"Separable Verbs at the Restaurant",text:"Two new separable verbs:\n\nmitbringen: Ich bringe Wein mit.\nmitnehmen: Ich nehme den Kaffee mit.\n\nWith modals, the prefix stays attached:\nIch kann Wein mitbringen.\nIch will den Kaffee mitnehmen.\n\nThe modal bracket keeps separable verbs whole!"},
{type:"teach",trg:"Ich hätte gern...",src:"I would gladly have...",pos:"intj",gender:null,note:"More formal and elegant than Ich möchte.\nUsed in upscale restaurants.",example:"A: Was hätten Sie gern?\nB: Ich hätte gern den Lachs.\nA: Ausgezeichnet!",exampleSrc:"A: What would you like?\nB: I would like the salmon.\nA: Excellent!",funFact:"'Hätte' = would have (Konjunktiv II). 'Gern' = gladly. Together they form the most elegant ordering phrase in German. Waiters notice the difference."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Getrennt oder zusammen?",src:"Separate or together? (the bill)",pos:"intj",gender:null,note:"The waiter asks this when you want to pay.\nGetrennt = each person pays their own.",example:"A: Zahlen bitte!\nB: Getrennt oder zusammen?\nA: Getrennt, bitte.",exampleSrc:"A: The bill please!\nB: Separate or together?\nA: Separate, please.",funFact:"Germans often split the bill individually (getrennt zahlen). This is completely normal and not considered rude, unlike in many other cultures."},
{type:"tip",title:"Restaurant Etiquette in Germany",text:"A few customs that differ from other countries:\n\n1. Seating: You seat yourself unless a sign says Bitte warten.\n2. Water: Not automatically free. Tap water is rarely served.\n3. Tipping: Round up or add 10%. Say the total when paying.\n4. Bill: Germans often split individually (Getrennt zahlen).\n5. Payment: Zahlen Sie bar oder mit Karte? (Cash or card?)",deepDive:{title:"Bar oder Karte? German payment culture",text:"Germany remains strongly cash-oriented compared to most of Western Europe. Many restaurants, bakeries, and small shops are Nur Bar (cash only).\n\nWhen paying, you tell the waiter the exact amount: Stimmt so (= keep the change). Or: Machen Sie 23 Euro (= make it 23 euros, the rest is a tip).\n\nThis direct approach with tipping is normal and not considered impolite."}},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} einen Kaffee zum {2}.",blanks:{"1":"möchte","2":"Mitnehmen"},pool:["möchte","Mitnehmen","kann","Essen"],hint:"I'd like a coffee TO GO.",sSrc:"I would like a coffee to go."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Das Essen ___! Wunderbar!'",opts:["riecht","schmeckt","kocht","bestellt"],ans:"schmeckt",hint:"He is eating it now. It is about the TASTE."},
{type:"fb",s:"Am Samstag {1} wir im Garten.",a:["grillen"],opts:["grillen","kochen","bestellen","essen"],hint:"Outside, with charcoal. A German summer tradition.",sSrc:"On Saturday we grill in the garden."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Lukas {1} das Schnitzel und Verumius {2} den Schweinebraten {3}.",blanks:{"1":"bestellt","2":"möchte","3":"bestellen"},pool:["bestellt","möchte","bestellen","kann","kochen","empfiehlt"],hint:"Lukas orders (conjugated). Verumius would LIKE to order (modal + infinitive).",sSrc:"Lukas orders the schnitzel and Verumius would like to order the pork roast."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich bringe morgen Kuchen mit.' Where does the prefix go?",opts:["Before the verb","At the end of the sentence","After the subject","It doesn't separate"],ans:"At the end of the sentence",hint:"Separable verbs: prefix to the end."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"bestellen",src:"to order"},{trg:"empfehlen",src:"to recommend"},{trg:"schmecken",src:"to taste"},{trg:"riechen",src:"to smell"},{trg:"kochen",src:"to cook"},{trg:"grillen",src:"to grill"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich {1} Bier mit. Wir trinken zusammen!",a:["bringe"],opts:["bringe","nehme","koche","bestelle"],hint:"Bringing something along to share. Separable: prefix at end.",sSrc:"I bring beer along. We drink together!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius asks the waiter: 'Was ___ Sie?'",opts:["bestellen","schmecken","kochen","empfehlen"],ans:"empfehlen",hint:"He is asking for a recommendation. Formal Sie = infinitive form."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"triumphant",art:"de-gasthaus-food-arriving",trg:"Das Essen kommt. Kartoffelpuffer mit Apfelmus. Lukas' Schnitzel ist so groß wie der Teller.",src:"The food arrives. Kartoffelpuffer with applesauce. Lukas's Schnitzel is as big as the plate."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"content",art:"de-gasthaus-food-arriving",trg:"Na? Wie schmeckt's?",src:"Well? How does it taste?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"delighted",art:"de-gasthaus-food-close",trg:"Das ist... sehr gut. Wirklich sehr gut!",src:"This is... really good. Really, really good!"}
]},

// ─── L6: Aus der Küche, mit Liebe ───
{id:"deu_r5l6",title:"Aus der Küche, mit Liebe",icon:"🏨",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Aus der Küche, mit Liebe",desc:"Seven prepositions that ALWAYS take dative. Plus hotel vocabulary. Lukas mentions he works 'bei einer Firma.' Every sentence has one of these little words.",goals:["7 dative prepositions: aus/bei/mit/nach/seit/von/zu","Hotel vocabulary","Dative article changes"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"calm",art:"de-gasthaus-interior-wide",trg:"Die Teller sind leer. Der Kellner kommt mit einem kleinen Zettel.",src:"The plates are empty. The waiter comes with a small slip of paper."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"dramatic",art:"de-gasthaus-waiter-bill",trg:"Der Kellner sieht die beiden an und fragt:",src:"The waiter looks at the two of them and asks:"},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"matter-of-fact",art:"de-gasthaus-waiter-bill",trg:"Zusammen oder getrennt? Das heißt: eine Rechnung oder zwei?",src:"Zusammen oder getrennt? That means: one bill or two?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"confused",art:"de-gasthaus-interior-table",trg:"Getrennt, bitte. Moment, ich habe meine Karte...",src:"Separate, please. One moment, I have my card..."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"ominous",art:"de-gasthaus-waiter-bill",trg:"Der Kellner schüttelt den Kopf. Nur Bargeld.",src:"The waiter shakes his head. Cash only."},
{type:"tip",title:"Dative Prepositions: The Magic 7",text:"Seven prepositions ALWAYS take dative:\n\naus: out of / from (origin)\nbei: at / near / with (someone's place)\nmit: with\nnach: after / to (cities, countries)\nseit: since / for (time)\nvon: from / of / by\nzu: to (people, places, events)\n\nMnemonic: 'Aus-bei-mit, nach-seit, von-zu'\nSing it like a chant. Germans learn it this way too.",deepDive:{title:"How Dative Changes Articles",text:"der becomes dem, die becomes der, das becomes dem, plural die becomes den (+n on noun). Masculine and neuter look the same in dative: dem/einem. You already know accusative (den/einen). Dative is the 'receiver' case."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Dative Articles After Prepositions",groups:[{label:"Definite",rows:[{pronoun:"masculine (der)",form:"dem",src:"mit dem Mann"},{pronoun:"feminine (die)",form:"der",src:"mit der Frau"},{pronoun:"neuter (das)",form:"dem",src:"mit dem Kind"},{pronoun:"plural (die)",form:"den (+n)",src:"mit den Kindern"}]},{label:"Indefinite",rows:[{pronoun:"masculine (ein)",form:"einem",src:"mit einem Mann"},{pronoun:"feminine (eine)",form:"einer",src:"mit einer Frau"},{pronoun:"neuter (ein)",form:"einem",src:"mit einem Kind"}]}],note:"Masculine and neuter look the same in dative: dem/einem."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich komme aus ___ Küche.' (die Küche)",opts:["die","der","dem","den"],ans:"der",hint:"Küche is feminine. After 'aus' (dative), die becomes der."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Essen kommt aus {1} Küche.",a:["der"],opts:["der","die","dem","den"],hint:"'Aus' always demands the same case. What happens to 'die' in that case?",sSrc:"The food comes from the kitchen."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich esse mit ___ Freund.' (ein Freund)",opts:["einem","einen","einer","ein"],ans:"einem",hint:"Mit requires dative case. Masculine dative ein form?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Nach {1} Essen gehen wir spazieren.",a:["dem"],opts:["dem","das","den","der"],hint:"Neuter noun after nach. Dative case changes the article.",sSrc:"After the meal we go for a walk."},
{type:"teach",trg:"übernachten",src:"to stay overnight",note:"Regular. Über (over) + Nacht (night) = to overnight somewhere.",example:"A: Wo übernachtest du?\nB: Ich übernachte in einem Hotel.",exampleSrc:"A: Where are you staying overnight?\nB: I'm staying in a hotel.",funFact:"Works for hotels, hostels, friends' couches. 'Übernachtung' = overnight stay. Every booking site uses it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Einzelzimmer",src:"the single room",note:"Neuter. Einzel (single) + Zimmer (room).",example:"A: Haben Sie ein Einzelzimmer?\nB: Ja, für wie viele Nächte?",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a single room?\nB: Yes, for how many nights?",funFact:"At German hotel reception: 'Ein Einzelzimmer, bitte.' Compound words are your friends now."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Doppelzimmer",src:"the double room",note:"Neuter. Doppel (double) + Zimmer (room).",example:"A: Ich möchte ein Doppelzimmer.\nB: Mit Frühstück?",exampleSrc:"A: I would like a double room.\nB: With breakfast?",funFact:"Can mean twin beds OR a double bed. Specify 'mit Doppelbett' if you need the big bed."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Rezeption",src:"the reception / front desk",note:"Feminine. Same word as English, German pronunciation.",example:"A: Fragen Sie an der Rezeption.\nB: Danke, ich gehe sofort hin.",exampleSrc:"A: Ask at the reception.\nB: Thanks, I'll go right away.",funFact:"The go-to place for complaints, key cards, and asking 'Wo ist das WLAN?'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Halbpension",src:"half board (breakfast + dinner)",note:"Feminine. Halb (half) + Pension (board).",example:"A: Ist das mit Halbpension?\nB: Ja, Frühstück und Abendessen inklusive.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that with half board?\nB: Yes, breakfast and dinner included.",funFact:"Vollpension = full board (all meals). Halbpension is the sweet spot: breakfast and dinner at the hotel, lunch on your own."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius braucht ein Zimmer für eine Person. Was braucht er?",opts:["ein Einzelzimmer","ein Doppelzimmer","die Halbpension","die Rezeption"],ans:"ein Einzelzimmer",hint:"Single person = single room."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich übernachte in {1} Hotel.",a:["einem"],opts:["einem","ein","einer","einen"],hint:"Neuter noun. In + dative for location. Dative ein form?",sSrc:"I am staying overnight in a hotel."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Er wohnt seit {1} Jahr bei {2} Freund.",blanks:{"1":"einem","2":"einem"},pool:["einem","einer","einen","dem","der"],hint:"Two dative prepositions in a row. Both nouns are masculine or neuter. Apply the dative indefinite article rule.",sSrc:"He has been living for a year with a friend."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich gehe zu ___ Rezeption.' (die Rezeption)",opts:["die","dem","den","der"],ans:"der",hint:"Rezeption is feminine. After 'zu' (dative), die becomes der."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Brot kommt von {1} Bäckerei.",a:["der"],opts:["der","die","dem","den"],hint:"'Von' demands the same case as 'aus.' Apply it to a feminine noun.",sSrc:"The bread comes from the bakery."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Nach {1} Frühstück gehen wir zu {2} Rezeption und fragen nach {3} Einzelzimmer.",blanks:{"1":"dem","2":"der","3":"einem"},pool:["dem","der","einem","den","die","ein"],hint:"Three different dative prepositions. Match each noun's gender to the correct dative article form.",sSrc:"After the breakfast we go to the reception and ask about a single room."},
{type:"teach",trg:"seit",src:"since / for (time duration)",pos:"prep",gender:null,note:"Dative preposition. Seit drei Wochen = for three weeks.",example:"A: Seit wann lernst du Deutsch?\nB: Seit einem Monat.",exampleSrc:"A: Since when have you been learning German?\nB: For one month.",funFact:"German uses present tense with seit: Ich lerne seit einem Monat Deutsch = I have been learning German for a month. English switches to perfect, German stays present."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which preposition means 'since' or 'for' (time)?",opts:["von","seit","aus","nach"],ans:"seit",hint:"Which dative preposition indicates duration or starting point in time?"},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"aus",src:"out of / from"},{trg:"bei",src:"at / near / with"},{trg:"mit",src:"with"},{trg:"nach",src:"after / to"},{trg:"seit",src:"since / for"},{trg:"von",src:"from / of"},{trg:"zu",src:"to"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich möchte ein Doppelzimmer mit {1}.",a:["Halbpension"],opts:["Halbpension","Rezeption","Einzelzimmer","Frühstück"],hint:"Breakfast AND dinner included. Half of all meals.",sSrc:"I would like a double room with half board."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Aus-bei-mit, nach-seit, von-zu' all have in common:",opts:["They always take dative case","They always take accusative case","They are modal verbs","They are separable prefixes"],ans:"They always take dative case",hint:"The magic 7 chant. These prepositions all demand the same case."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"panicking",art:"de-gasthaus-interior-table",trg:"Ich habe kein Bargeld. Der nächste Automat ist... achthundert Meter? Oh nein.",src:"I have no cash. The nearest ATM is... eight hundred meters? Oh no."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"relaxed",art:"de-gasthaus-lukas-close",trg:"Ach, quatsch. Ich mach das. Ist doch nicht schlimm.",src:"Oh, nonsense. I got it. It's no big deal."}
]},

// ─── L7: Zusammen oder Getrennt? ───
{id:"deu_r5l7",title:"Zusammen oder Getrennt?",icon:"💰",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Zusammen oder Getrennt?",desc:"The big moment. Verumius must order, eat, and pay. What could go wrong? All grammar constructs in communicative action.",goals:["Order food in a restaurant","Express likes and abilities","Survive paying the bill"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"grateful",art:"de-gasthaus-interior-table",trg:"Lukas, das ist sehr nett. Ich gebe dir das Geld morgen!",src:"Lukas, that's very kind. I'll give you the money tomorrow!"},
{type:"tip",title:"Scene: Ordering",text:"Kellner: 'Was möchten Sie bestellen?'\nVerumius looks at Lukas. Lukas nods encouragingly.\nVerumius: 'Ich möchte... den... Schweine...braten?'\nKellner: 'Sehr gute Wahl! Und zu trinken?'\nVerumius: 'Ein Wasser, bitte.'\nKellner: 'Still oder mit Kohlensäure?'\nVerumius: '...'\nLukas: 'Zwei Sprudel, bitte.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"You are at a restaurant and want to order politely. Which phrase is correct?",opts:["Ich will Schweinebraten!","Gib mir Schweinebraten.","Schweinebraten, schnell!","Ich möchte den Schweinebraten, bitte."],ans:"Ich möchte den Schweinebraten, bitte.",hint:"The subjunctive form of mögen is the polite ordering formula."},
{type:"fb",s:"Und zu {1}, bitte?",a:["trinken"],opts:["trinken","essen","bestellen","kochen"],hint:"The waiter is asking about drinks. 'And to ___?'",sSrc:"And to drink, please?"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} bitte die Speisekarte {2}, und dann {3} ich {4}.",blanks:{"1":"möchte","2":"haben","3":"kann","4":"bestellen"},pool:["möchte","haben","kann","bestellen","will","essen"],hint:"I'd LIKE to HAVE the menu, then I CAN order. Two modal brackets.",sSrc:"I would like to please have the menu, and then I can order."},
{type:"mc",q:"Lukas: 'Schmeckt's?' Verumius sagt:",opts:["Ich kann nicht schmecken.","Es riecht gut.","Es schmeckt wunderbar!","Ich will schmecken."],ans:"Es schmeckt wunderbar!",hint:"He is eating and it tastes great."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich esse {1} Schweinebraten als Fisch.",a:["lieber"],opts:["lieber","besser","gern","am besten"],hint:"Expressing preference between two things. Comparative of gern.",sSrc:"I prefer to eat pork roast than fish."},
{type:"tip",title:"Scene: The Bill",text:"The meal is over. Verumius is zufrieden.\nKellner: 'Zusammen oder getrennt?'\nVerumius freezes. Together or separate? The food? The table? His life?\nLukas whispers: 'Er fragt, ob wir zusammen oder getrennt bezahlen.'\nVerumius: 'Ah! Zusammen!'\nHe reaches for his card. The waiter shakes his head.\n'Nur Bargeld.'\nVerumius has no cash."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Zusammen oder getrennt?' asks about:",opts:["sitting together or apart","paying together or splitting the bill","eating here or taking away","ordering one dish or two"],ans:"paying together or splitting the bill",hint:"Zusammen = together. Getrennt = separated. Think about the check."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Nur Bargeld' means the restaurant accepts:",opts:["only cards","only euros","only coins","only cash"],ans:"only cash",hint:"Bar = ___. Geld = money. What does Bargeld mean for payment?"},
{type:"fb",s:"Verumius {1} nicht bezahlen. Er hat kein Bargeld.",a:["kann"],opts:["kann","will","muss","darf"],hint:"He is NOT ABLE to pay. An ability problem.",sSrc:"Verumius cannot pay. He has no cash."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Lukas: 'Ich {1} für uns beide {2}. Du {3} mir morgen das Geld {4}.'",blanks:{"1":"kann","2":"bezahlen","3":"kannst","4":"mitbringen"},pool:["kann","bezahlen","kannst","mitbringen","muss","geben"],hint:"Lukas CAN pay for both. Verumius CAN bring the money tomorrow.",sSrc:"Lukas: 'I can pay for both of us. You can bring me the money tomorrow.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"How does Verumius say he LIKES the food?",opts:["Ich kann das Essen!","Ich muss das Essen!","Das Essen schmeckt mir!","Das Essen gefällt mir schlecht!"],ans:"Das Essen schmeckt mir!",hint:"Schmecken + dative = tastes good to me."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich mag das Restaurant. Es {1} mir hier.",a:["gefällt"],opts:["gefällt","schmeckt","kann","will"],hint:"The restaurant is pleasing TO ME. Gefallen with dative.",sSrc:"I like the restaurant. It pleases me here."},
{type:"tip",title:"Scene: Walking Home",text:"Lukas and Verumius walk through the evening streets.\nLukas: 'Woher kommst du?'\nVerumius: 'Aus den Niederlanden. Ich bin seit einer Woche hier.'\nLukas: 'Nur eine Woche? Du kannst schon gut bestellen!'\nVerumius laughs. He has a friend now. A real one.\nLukas: 'Hier, meine Nummer. Wir können zusammen Deutsch üben.'\nVerumius: 'Das ist lieb von dir.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"'Woher kommst du?' asks about:",opts:["where you are going","where you come from","what you want","how you feel"],ans:"where you come from",hint:"Woher = from where. The standard way to ask about origin."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich bin seit {1} Woche in Deutschland.",a:["einer"],opts:["einer","eine","einem","ein"],hint:"Seit = dative. Woche is feminine. Dative form of eine?",sSrc:"I have been in Germany for a week."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Lukas kommt aus {1} Stadt und arbeitet bei {2} Firma.",blanks:{"1":"der","2":"einer"},pool:["der","einer","dem","die","einem","ein"],hint:"Both nouns are feminine. Apply the dative article rule for feminine nouns with both a definite and an indefinite article.",sSrc:"Lukas comes from the city and works at a company."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich ___ jetzt besser bestellen!'",opts:["muss","darf","soll","kann"],ans:"kann",hint:"He has improved! He is now ABLE to order."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das war das {1} Essen in Deutschland!",a:["beste"],opts:["beste","bessere","gute","wunderbare"],hint:"Superlative: gut, besser, am ___. After das, what form?",sSrc:"That was the best food in Germany!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Three levels of liking:",opts:["gern < gefallen < lieben","können < müssen < wollen","schmecken < riechen < kochen","bestellen < empfehlen < mitbringen"],ans:"gern < gefallen < lieben",hint:"Like < be pleased by < love."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"sincere",art:"de-gasthaus-exit",trg:"Alter, entspann dich. Du bist neu hier. So läuft das unter Freunden.",src:"Dude, relax. You're new here. That's how it works between friends."}
]},

// ─── L8: Stammtisch-Prüfung ───
{id:"deu_r5l8",title:"Stammtisch-Prüfung",icon:"🍻",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Stammtisch-Prüfung",desc:"Verumius returns to the Gasthaus. This time, he is ready. Lukas saved him a seat at the Stammtisch. Full unit review.",goals:["All 6 modals in context","Dative prepositions mastery","Full restaurant communicative skills"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"peaceful",art:"de-berlin-street-night",trg:"Draußen. Eine kühle Berliner Nacht. Laternen. Lukas schiebt sein Lastenrad langsam neben Verumius her.",src:"Outside. A cool Berlin night. Streetlamps. Lukas pushes his cargo bike slowly alongside Verumius."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"casual",art:"de-berlin-street-night",trg:"Hier, gib mir deine Nummer. Ich schreib dir, wenn ich wieder in der Gegend bin.",src:"Here, give me your number. I'll text you when I'm in the area again."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"moved",art:"de-berlin-street-night",trg:"Danke, Lukas. Für alles. Das Essen, das Geld, die Hilfe.",src:"Thank you, Lukas. For everything. The food, the money, the help."},
{type:"mc",q:"Der Kellner: 'Was ___ Sie trinken?'",opts:["können","müssen","möchten","sollen"],ans:"möchten",hint:"The polite way to ask what someone wants."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich möchte die {1}, bitte.",a:["Speisekarte"],opts:["Speisekarte","Zigarette","Rezeption","Halbpension"],hint:"You need this to see what is available to eat.",sSrc:"I would like the menu, please."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich kann jetzt die Speisekarte lesen!' Verumius expresses:",opts:["He must read the menu.","He is able to read the menu now.","He wants to read the menu.","He should read the menu."],ans:"He is able to read the menu now.",hint:"Können = ability. He has learned!"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Ich {1} den Schweinebraten {2}, und mein Freund {3} die Käsespätzle {4}.",blanks:{"1":"möchte","2":"bestellen","3":"will","4":"haben"},pool:["möchte","bestellen","will","haben","kann","essen"],hint:"One speaker is polite, the other direct. Two different modals + infinitive at end.",sSrc:"I would like to order the pork roast, and my friend wants to have the cheese spaetzle."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Essen {1} wunderbar!",a:["schmeckt"],opts:["schmeckt","riecht","kocht","bestellt"],hint:"You are eating it. The taste is wonderful.",sSrc:"The food tastes wonderful!"},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich trinke lieber Bier.' means:",opts:["I drink better beer.","I prefer beer.","I drink the best beer.","I can drink beer."],ans:"I prefer beer.",hint:"Lieber = preferably. Comparative of gern."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Das Brot kommt aus {1} Küche und das Bier kommt von {2} Brauerei.",blanks:{"1":"der","2":"der"},pool:["der","dem","die","den","einer","einem"],hint:"Both Küche and Brauerei are feminine. Dative: die becomes der.",sSrc:"The bread comes from the kitchen and the beer comes from the brewery."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Darf man hier rauchen?' 'Nein, das ist ___.'",opts:["einfach","lustig","wunderbar","verboten"],ans:"verboten",hint:"Forbidden! Not allowed."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich wohne seit {1} Monat in Deutschland.",a:["einem"],opts:["einem","ein","einen","einer"],hint:"Seit = dative. Monat is masculine. Dative form of ein?",sSrc:"I have been living in Germany for a month."},
{type:"mc",q:"Which sentence uses modal + separable verb correctly?",opts:["Ich kann Wein mitbringen.","Ich kann Wein bringe mit.","Ich mitbringe kann Wein.","Ich bringe kann Wein mit."],ans:"Ich kann Wein mitbringen.",hint:"With modals, separable verbs stay as one infinitive at the end."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Er {1} nicht {2}, weil es {3} ist.",blanks:{"1":"darf","2":"rauchen","3":"verboten"},pool:["darf","rauchen","verboten","kann","essen","schlecht"],hint:"He is not ALLOWED to smoke because it is forbidden.",sSrc:"He may not smoke, because it is forbidden."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Atmosphäre {1} mir sehr gut.",a:["gefällt"],opts:["gefällt","schmeckt","mag","kann"],hint:"The atmosphere is pleasing TO ME. Subject = atmosphere.",sSrc:"The atmosphere pleases me very much."},
{type:"mc",q:"The waiter asks how you want to pay. You prefer one shared bill. What do you say?",opts:["Getrennt, bitte.","Alles, bitte.","Bargeld, bitte.","Zusammen, bitte."],ans:"Zusammen, bitte.",hint:"The adverb for 'all in one' is the opposite of getrennt."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"können",src:"can/able to"},{trg:"müssen",src:"must/have to"},{trg:"dürfen",src:"may/allowed"},{trg:"wollen",src:"to want"},{trg:"sollen",src:"should"},{trg:"mögen",src:"to like"}]},
{type:"fb",s:"Ich übernachte in {1} Hotel mit Halbpension.",a:["einem"],opts:["einem","ein","einer","einen"],hint:"Neuter noun. In + dative for location. Dative ein form?",sSrc:"I am staying overnight in a hotel with half board."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Nach {1} Essen gehen wir zu {2} Hotel und fragen an {3} Rezeption nach {4} Einzelzimmer.",blanks:{"1":"dem","2":"dem","3":"der","4":"einem"},pool:["dem","dem","der","einem","den","einer"],hint:"Four dative prepositions: nach, zu, an, nach again. Match each noun's gender to the correct dative article. Three are neuter, one is feminine.",sSrc:"After the meal we go to the hotel and ask at the reception about a single room."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich ___ jetzt gut bestellen, aber ich ___ noch besser Deutsch lernen.'",opts:["muss ... kann","kann ... muss","will ... darf","soll ... mag"],ans:"kann ... muss",hint:"He CAN order (ability), but MUST learn more (necessity)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das ist das {1} Restaurant in der Stadt!",a:["beste"],opts:["beste","besser","gut","lieber"],hint:"The superlative form of gut. After das?",sSrc:"That is the best restaurant in the city!"},
{type:"mc",q:"Which preposition means 'with'?",opts:["bei","mit","von","aus"],ans:"mit",hint:"The most common dative preposition. Used constantly."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Lukas {1} gern zu Hause, aber heute {2} er lieber im Restaurant {3}.",blanks:{"1":"kocht","2":"möchte","3":"essen"},pool:["kocht","möchte","essen","kann","will","kochen"],hint:"Lukas likes cooking at home, but today he'd rather eat out.",sSrc:"Lukas cooks at home, but today he would like to eat out."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Ich esse gern Fisch, lieber Fleisch, am liebsten Schweinebraten.' shows:",opts:["drei Modalverben","gern to lieber to am liebsten (three levels)","drei Restaurants","Dativpräpositionen"],ans:"gern to lieber to am liebsten (three levels)",hint:"Three levels of preference: from basic to stronger to strongest."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"aus",src:"out of/from"},{trg:"bei",src:"at/near/with"},{trg:"nach",src:"after/to"},{trg:"seit",src:"since/for"},{trg:"von",src:"from/of"},{trg:"zu",src:"to"}]},
{type:"tip",title:"Unit 5 Complete: Zusammen!",text:"Verumius came to the Gasthaus hungry and confused.\nHe left with:\n\n1. A best friend (Lukas)\n2. Six modal verbs\n3. Seven dative prepositions\n4. The ability to order food and (almost) pay the bill\n5. A love for Schweinebraten\n\nNext: Verumius explores Berlin. What could POSSIBLY go wrong?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"hopeful",art:"de-berlin-street-night-wide",trg:"Lukas winkt, steigt auf sein Rad und fährt in die Nacht. Verumius steht da und lächelt. Berlin fühlt sich ein kleines bisschen mehr wie Zuhause an.",src:"Lukas waves, gets on his bike, and rides into the night. Verumius stands there and smiles. Berlin feels a little bit more like home."}
]},

]};

export default UNIT_5;
